[[File:Nenbutsuji-yama Kofun, haisho-1.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|{{ill|Emperor Kaika|ja|開化天皇|12=draft}}'s Kasuga Itsukawa Sakaue Mausoleum]]
'''Nenbutsuji-yama Kofun''' (念仏寺山古墳) is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Aburakōji-chō|ja|油阪町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft}}. It is Historic Site1 by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} as the "'''Kasuga Itsukawa Sakaue Mausoleum'''" (春日率川坂上陵) and attributed to {{ill|Emperor Kaika|ja|開化天皇|12=draft}}, the 9th emperor of Japan.

== Overview ==

This large keyhole-shaped tumulus is located in central Nara City, between {{ill|Sanjo Street|ja|三条通り|12=draft}} and Aburakōji Street.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nara City Historical Records, Archaeology Volume|publisher=吉川弘文館|year=1971|pages=82-85}}</ref> It has not undergone extensive excavation due to its Historic Site as an imperial mausoleum by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}}.

The tumulus is oriented south-southeast. During the {{ill|Early Modern built|ja|近世|12=draft}}, the tumulus fell under the temple grounds of {{ill|Nenbutsuji Temple (Nara City)|ja|念仏寺 (奈良市)|12=draft}} and was utilized as a cemetery, leading to mound alterations. In the late Edo period, cemetery relocation and restoration of the mausoleum took place.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nara Prefecture Archaeological History|publisher=奈良県立橿原考古学研究所|year=2001}}</ref> Current features include flattened tops of the circular and trapezoidal sections, and the mound's original stepped construction is no longer evident.

=== burial goods and Age ===
Fragments of cylindrical haniwa discovered on the western embankment suggest that the tumulus was constructed in the early 5th century (middle {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}}).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Historical Atlas of Japan|publisher=平凡社|year=1981}}</ref> Excavations in 1975 and 2008 uncovered Edo-period burial burial goods, including ossuary vessels and wooden coffins.<ref>[http://www.47news.jp/CN/200812/CN2008121101000797.html "burial goods from Edo built Uncovered near Emperor Kaika's Mausoleum"] (Kyodo News, December 11, 2008).</ref>

During the construction of {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京|12=draft}}, many ancient Kofuns were destroyed. However, Nenbutsuji-yama Kofun and a few others, such as the {{ill|Hōraisan Kofun|ja|宝来山古墳|1=Hōraiyama Kofun|12=draft}}, survived.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130615225332/http://www.47news.jp/CN/201303/CN2013032501001891.html "Ancient Tombs Destroyed for Heijō-kyō built"] (Kyodo News, March 25, 2013).</ref>

== Archaeological Record ==
* Meiji built: Designated as Emperor Kaika’s mausoleum by the Imperial Household Agency.
* 1975: Excavation during torii reconstruction revealed Edo-period burial items.
* 1976: Pre-construction survey of embankments.
* 1988: Structural maintenance of protective fencing and gates.
* 2002: Investigations during road construction.
* 2008: Reconstruction of torii uncovered ossuary vessels, wooden coffins, and human remains.

== Mound area ==
* Total length: Approx. 100 meters
* Rear circular mound:
** Diameter: Approx. 48 meters
** Height: Approx. 8 meters
* Front trapezoidal mound:
** Width: Approx. 48 meters
** Height: Approx. 6 meters

== Interred_individual ==
The actual individual interred at Nenbutsuji-yama Kofun is unknown. However, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} designates it as the mausoleum of Emperor Kaika, the 9th emperor of Japan.<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html List of Imperial Mausolea - Imperial Household Agency]</ref> Ancient records, such as the *{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}* and *{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}*, reference the location as "Kasuga Itsukawa Sakaue," supporting this identification. However, Emperor Kaika and other rulers of the {{ill|Eight Undocumented Sovereigns|ja|欠史八代|12=draft}} are considered mythological or semi-legendary figures.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kasuga Itsukawa Sakaue Mausoleum Overview|publisher=平凡社|year=2006}}</ref>

